# Animal Detection using ML and Deep Learning

An image classification project that identifies animal species from photos using transfer learning. CNN-extracted features (via a pretrained MobileNetV2) are fed into traditional ML classifiers (SVM and Random Forest), comparing how each performs on top of the same deep feature representation.

## Dataset

- 6 animal classes: **hyena, fox, wolf, tiger, cheetah, lion**
- 5,169 total images (multiple resolutions per class: 224px, 300px, 512px)
- 80/20 train-test split

## Approach

Rather than training a CNN end-to-end, this project uses **transfer learning for feature extraction**:

1. Images are resized to 128×128 and passed through **MobileNetV2** (pretrained on ImageNet, top classification layer removed)
2. A `GlobalAveragePooling2D` layer converts the CNN's feature maps into a single 1,280-dimensional feature vector per image
3. These CNN-extracted features (not raw pixels) are used to train two separate classifiers:
   - **Support Vector Machine** (RBF kernel, C=10)
   - **Random Forest** (200 estimators)
4. Each classifier is evaluated on the held-out test set with accuracy, confusion matrix, and a full classification report

## Results

| Model | Accuracy |
|---|---|
| CNN (MobileNetV2) + SVM | **99.42%** |
| CNN (MobileNetV2) + Random Forest | **99.23%** |

Both models achieved per-class precision, recall, and F1-scores between 0.97 and 1.00 across all 6 animal classes, with no class showing a significant weak spot. SVM slightly outperformed Random Forest, though the margin is small enough that either is a strong choice on this feature representation.

## Tech stack

- **Python**
- **TensorFlow / Keras** — MobileNetV2 pretrained model, feature extraction
- **scikit-learn** — SVM, Random Forest, train/test split, evaluation metrics
- **OpenCV** — image loading and resizing
- **Matplotlib / Seaborn** — confusion matrices and result visualization
- **Google Colab** — development and training environment (GPU-backed)

## How to run

1. Open the desired notebook (`ANIMAL_PREDICTION__SVM_CNN.ipynb` or `Animal_prediction_Randomforest_CNN.ipynb`) in Google Colab
2. Mount Google Drive and place `animal_dataset.zip` in `MyDrive/dataset/`
3. Run all cells — the notebook will unzip the dataset, extract CNN features, train the classifier, and output accuracy plus a confusion matrix and classification report

## Why CNN features + classical ML instead of an end-to-end CNN?

Training a CNN from scratch needs a large dataset to avoid overfitting. By using MobileNetV2's pretrained ImageNet features as a fixed feature extractor, this approach gets strong, general-purpose visual features without needing to train millions of parameters from scratch — then lets a lightweight classifier (SVM or Random Forest) learn the decision boundary on top. This is a practical, resource-efficient approach to image classification on a moderately sized dataset.

## What I'd improve next

- Fine-tune the last few MobileNetV2 layers instead of using it purely as a frozen feature extractor, to see if accuracy improves further
- Add a held-out validation set (currently only train/test) to better guard against overfitting to the test set
- Complete and fix the Decision Tree comparison (the current version has a data-loading bug and doesn't run end-to-end) to get a genuine three-way comparison
- Test on images outside the original dataset distribution to check real-world generalization
